issue.title: What text editor/editor plugin do you use for JSDoc comments?
issue.body:
I'm interested what tools you use for adding such comments:

```js
/**
 * Foo
 * @param {Object} fooParam Description
 * @constructor
 */
...
```

issue.title: module myModule as './path/to/module'; outputs "Semi-colon expected" error
issue.body:
I've been trying to bring in a module as a single object using  
```js
module myModule as './path/to/module';
```
but I get the following error ```Semi-colon expected```

Is this because it's not implemented yet or am I doing something wrong?

my current work around is to replace the line with 
```js
var myModule = System.get("relative/path/to/module");
```

pull_request.title: Wearable: fixes for feedback notification.
pull_request.body:
* Moved "Rate this session" action from notification Activity's onClick to the notification Action - I think this is more intuitive and in line with Wear platform; additionally shows how to add actions to the Wear notification.
* Set custom size preset for the feedback notification (SIZE_LARGE). Before that, in case of session title in two lines, room number and speaker name were not visible.

issue.title: module myModule as './path/to/module'; outputs "Semi-colon expected" error
issue.body:
I've been trying to bring in a module as a single object using  
```js
module myModule as './path/to/module';
```
but I get the following error ```Semi-colon expected```

Is this because it's not implemented yet or am I doing something wrong?

my current work around is to replace the line with 
```js
var myModule = System.get("relative/path/to/module");
```

comment.body:
You are doing something wrong. The new syntax is
```js
import * as myModule from './path/to/module';
```
Where did you read about the older syntax?

issue.title: Live stage for demo
issue.body:
Congrats, awesome project.

To increase adoption, I suggest you stage a live demo of [each layout](https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/tools/setup/setup_kit#pick-a-layout), quickly accessible from https://developers.google.com/web/starter-kit/, so developers can look at the it before downloading/installing/etc.
